	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Hundreds of University of Central Florida graduates celebrated with their families and friends Friday and Saturday during the first three commencement ceremonies at the new UCF Arena.</p>
<p>On Friday, Michelle G. Chandler, a doctoral student in Public Affairs, received the first UCF degree awarded in the 10,000-seat venue, which opened in September. UCF President John Hitt referred to the &quot;handsome new Arena&quot; in his welcome addresses on both days, and graduates and their families took several pictures outside with the front of the Arena in their background.</p>
<p>The Arena is part of the changing face of the north end of UCF&rsquo;s campus, which also includes Bright House Networks Stadium, four new residence halls, stores, restaurants and parking garages. The 10,000-seat Arena has hosted basketball games, concerts and other entertainment since it opened in September. With nearly double the seating capacity of the old Arena, the new facility has allowed UCF to reduce the number of ceremonies held each semester.</p>
<p>The new Arena wasn't the only first for UCF this weekend. Graduates wore newly designed caps and gowns with the UCF logo for all of the ceremonies.</p>
<p><embed width="425" quality="1" wmode="transparent" menu="menu" loop="loop" scale="ShowAll" height="366" src="http://www.youtube.com/cp/vjVQa1PpcFNrjlQrCgH70-
L8VwYVOMXJR5KYU2FxXms="></embed></p>
<p>More than 3,700 students expected to graduate this semester. Among the graduates, 3,029 students filed intent forms for bachelor&rsquo;s degrees, 626 for master&rsquo;s degrees, 11 for education specialist degrees and 80 for doctoral degrees. The total number of degrees awarded by UCF in its history is about 175,000.</p>
<p>On Saturday, state Rep. Dean Cannon, a Winter Park Republican who is in line to become speaker of the House, addressed graduates of the College of Business Administration, College of Engineering and Computer Science and the College of Optics and Photonics.</p>
<p>Cannon drew a loud round of applause after he told the crowd that it was the first time he had ever given a commencement address at&nbsp; &quot;a school that had just won a conference football championship.&quot; He then mentioned that it was the first time he had ever given a commencement address.</p>
<p>Cannon spoke of the great accomplishments of three of the nation's founding fathers -- Thomas Jefferson, James Madison and Alexander Hamilton. He said Jefferson had crafted the Declaration of Independence by age 33 and that Madison was a leader in Virginia's constitutional efforts by age 25. Hamilton was a top military officer and aide to George Washington before he turned 22, Cannon said.</p>
<p>Today's graduates, Cannon said, are the next group of accomplished and successful people who will lead our state and nation.</p>
<p>&quot;I ask you to make it a goal to make your state and nation a better place,&quot; he said.</p>
<p>UCF alumnus and Circuit Judge Walter Komanski was the featured speaker during the morning ceremony on Friday, which included graduates of the College of Education, College of Health and Public Affairs, College of Medicine and College of Nursing. He told students to find something they loved to do and to stick with it. He also told students to prioritize their lives and to not fear failure, but to learn from it.</p>
<p>The Friday afternoon ceremony featured students in the College of Arts and Humanities, the Rosen College of Hospitality Management, College of Sciences, Office of the Vice Provost, Undergraduate Studies and Graduate Studies. The speaker was Margot Knight, president and CEO of United Arts of Central Florida.</p>
<p>Web casts of each of the graduation ceremonies can be viewed at <a href="http://webcast.oir.ucf.edu">http://webcast.oir.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
<hr width="100%" size="2" />
<p>&nbsp;<strong>UCF Stands for Opportunity:</strong> Established in 1963, the University of Central Florida is a diverse metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th-largest in the country with more than 48,000 students. Located in Orlando, Fla., UCF offers high-quality undergraduate and graduate education, student development and continuing education, while conducting cutting-edge research that powers the region's economic development. For more UCF news, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
		
			
		
	
		
			
		
	
